  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (such as proceeds from drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other criminal activities) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This process disguises the origin of the money, making it seem like it came from a legal source.\n\nGovernments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering because it enables criminal activities to flourish, undermines financial systems, and can have destabilizing effects on economies. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prosecuted under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, among other laws. Similarly, the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an international body, sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CFT) efforts. Most countries have implemented AML laws in line with FATF recommendations.",
